<br>
While you can argue the legitimacy of the occupation of the land until the cows come home (or die), the farms themselves were well-managed, provided employment (black farm workers on these farms are being turfed out, raped, killed, etc, just as their white employers are) and produced a large amount of good-quality produce.<br>
<br>
The large farms are to be split up amongst the persons occupying them, and the reduction of such a large production area to a collection of peasant-style farms will have a hugely detrimental effect on the efficiency and quality of the crops produced. That is, except on the large farms that are being left as single entities and awarded to such superb farm managers as Mr. Mugabe's wife and other members of the Zimbabwe cabinet.<br>
<br>
Once production falls far enough (and it has already, due to the uncertainty of the last couple of years) the spectre of food shortages and starvation arise, with western (including US) money and produce being used to avert the crisis. As I've said, we can argue the politics of land grabs round and round. If the land was being used to benefit the country as well as provide the farmers with a living, then it is surely foolish to say that they are getting what they deserve due to past colonialism, when it will likely plummet that country into a nightmare of famine and death. <p><BR><BR>
