 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ucanielfaithealer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caniel Faithealer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/2/02 1:15:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1685.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Also</span><hr size=1> First, I must admit I know little of the past or current situation in Zimbabwe. However I do have limited knowledge of the history of it's eastern neighbor Mozambique, which until 1975 was a Portuguese colony.<br>
<br>
A little background. I am a first generation American of Portuguese decent. My mother has 6 brothers, 5 of which served in the Portuguese Army. All five were stationed in Mozambique in the late 60's to early 70's. Four of them will not talk about what they saw. My godfather spoke of it once when we were in Portugal and passed his old military base. I was 12 years old at the time and 16 years later I still remember his tale vividly.<br>
<br>
There was a civil uprising for independence starting in the late 60's growing more violent in the 70's. Your history books will mention that Portugal pulled out of Mozambique in 1975, but offer little explanation as to why. Anyhow, the Portuguese military was present for &quot;policing action&quot; during this time to put down the revolutionaries. How did they do this? If you were a suspected of being a member of Frelimo (the resistance group) you were tied to the back of a jeep. You were then dragged through the tall stiff plains grass which sliced through your skin like razors. Then they would pour salt water mixed with a bit of honey onto your woulds and dump your body on the nearest fire ant hill.<br>
<br>
At this point in his story, my mother interjected asking him to please stop, I was only 12. I asked him, years later, about what else happened during his time in Mozambique, but like my other uncles, he will not talk about what he saw... I scoured the history books to find out oddly enough they make little to no mention of the presence of the Portuguese Army (sarcasm).<br>
<br>
Makes me wonder what happened to the people of the Zimbabwe resistance groups and why they would want to tortue and kill the remaining colonists...<br>
<br>
For those not familiar with Mozambique it's immediately east of Zimbabwe and immediately North of South Africa.<br>
